1778538749780108	reckon-dev	itc:v3:AWLk8kz5M8ySZQAAAAAAQevVvre1WgAAAAEvvAE		item.create	bn-2xa	{"description":"**Problem:** After the first `reckon` run, subsequent runs show only events newly emitted by readers. Persisted events in `~/.cache/reckon/index.sqlite` (the `events` table) are written by `persist_events` but never read back. Combined with `plan_jsonl_scan` skipping unchanged files, this means the second invocation reports ~nothing.\n\nReproduction:\n1. `rm ~/.cache/reckon/index.sqlite && cargo run --bin reckon` — shows correct billions of tokens.\n2. `cargo run --bin reckon` (no further edits) — shows almost nothing.\n\nThis contradicts the architecture invariant in `ws/default/AGENTS.md`: \"Cost at display time, not at write time.\"\n\n**Scope:** `crates/reckon-readers/src/lib.rs` only.\n\n- Add a `load_events` query mirroring `load_source_files` (read every row from `events`, reconstruct `UsageEvent` including the `TokenCounts` fields, `dedup_key`, `month`, `provider`, `project`, `known_cost_usd`, `byok_usage_inference`).\n- In `run_readers_with_cache`, after the scan completes, merge persisted events with newly emitted events, deduping by `dedup_key`. Fresh events from this scan win (they may carry corrected fields).\n- Make sure `run_readers` (no cache) keeps its current behavior.\n- Existing tests must still pass; add a test that persists events in one Sink, opens a second cached Sink against the same path, runs a no-op reader, and asserts the cached events are returned.\n\n**Acceptance:**\n\n- Two back-to-back `cargo run --bin reckon` invocations produce identical totals (modulo any new agent activity in between).\n- `cargo test -p reckon-readers` passes.\n- No new dependencies.\n- Aggregation already dedups by `dedup_key`, so replay must use the same key.","kind":"bug","labels":["cache","correctness"],"size":"m","title":"Replay cached events on each run so totals don't decay to deltas"}	blake3:fxE8U7AUVRPG11Z--3r84TsTnlz3FvwGk17Y38j_ld4
1778538763954699	reckon-dev	itc:v3:AWLk8kz5M8ySZQAAAAAAQevVvre1WgAAAAEvvQE		item.create	bn-uwe	{"description":"**Problem:** `find_jsonl_files` in `crates/reckon-readers/src/claude.rs` calls `fs::read_dir` non-recursively, so it only sees top-level `<project>/*.jsonl`. Claude Code writes subagent transcripts under `<project>/<sessionId>/subagents/*.jsonl`. On this machine: 3526 of 4418 total JSONL files live in those subdirs — most are silently dropped.\n\nValidated cost gap vs ccusage for May 2026 Claude: reckon shows ~\\$2116, ccusage shows ~\\$2967. The subagent jsonls are the prime suspect.\n\n**Scope:** `crates/reckon-readers/src/claude.rs` only.\n\n- Replace `find_jsonl_files` with a recursive walker (depth-first or BFS) that collects every `*.jsonl` under the project dir. The walker must:\n  - Not follow symlinks.\n  - Skip directories silently on permission errors (consistent with existing fallthrough behavior).\n  - Preserve the existing path → project association (project is derived from the **top-level** project directory name, not the subdir name — so a subagent jsonl belongs to the parent project).\n- Reuse the existing `decode_project_name` for the top-level dir.\n- Add a unit test using a tempdir fixture that lays out:\n  - `<project>/abc.jsonl` (assistant entry, dedup key A)\n  - `<project>/sess1/subagents/agent-xxx.jsonl` (assistant entry, dedup key B)\n  - `<project>/sess1/subagents/agent-yyy.jsonl` (assistant entry, dedup key C)\n  Run the reader and assert all three events come through with the same `project`.\n\n**Acceptance:**\n- `cargo test -p reckon-readers claude` passes the new test plus existing ones.\n- After fix, a fresh-cache reckon run for `--source claude` reports more tokens than before; the May 2026 claude total moves measurably closer to ccusage's number.\n- No new dependencies (don't add `walkdir`; a small recursive function is enough).","kind":"bug","labels":["readers","claude"],"size":"s","title":"Claude reader misses subagent JSONLs in <session>/subagents/"}	blake3:QEsRmpvoUrT1HkrKi4K7xnWSu7ZQdgqbYV1aPZft9-M
1778538778922493	reckon-dev	itc:v3:AWLk8kz5M8ySZQAAAAAAQevVvre1WgAAAAEvvgE		item.create	bn-3hi	{"description":"**Problem:** Two compounding bugs make pricing always return \\$0 for unknown-family models even when their LiteLLM entries exist.\n\n1. `crates/reckon-core/src/pricing.rs::canonical_slug` requires the LiteLLM key to contain `/` or `.`. Keys like `gemini-3-flash-preview` and `gemini-3-pro-preview` have neither, so they never enter the pricing map.\n2. For keys that **do** have a dot, like `gemini-3.1-pro-preview`, `canonical_slug_from_dot` splits at the first `.` and emits `ModelSlug(\"gemini-3/1-pro-preview\")`. The reader emits `ModelSlug(\"gemini-3.1-pro-preview\")` (the raw `model_map` passthrough). Lookup misses.\n3. Same shape for `gpt-5.4` / `gpt-5.5` in `openai_canonical` — newer than the hard-coded `gpt-5.2`, so they pass through raw.\n\nCurrently emits the warning `priced at \\$0 (no pricing data): gemini-3-flash-preview, gemini-3-pro-preview, gemini-3.1-pro-preview, gpt-5.4, gpt-5.5` even though every one of those has a row in `pricing-fallback.json`.\n\n**Scope:**\n- `crates/reckon-core/src/pricing.rs` (primary).\n- `crates/reckon-core/src/model_map.rs` (secondary, may need updates).\n\nThe cleanest fix: keep canonical slugs lookup-friendly. Index pricing by **the exact slug the readers emit**, not a guessed vendor/model split. Approach:\n\n- For raw LiteLLM keys with no `/`: index them by themselves (`gemini-3-flash-preview` -> `ModelSlug(\"gemini-3-flash-preview\")`).\n- For raw LiteLLM keys with `/`: keep the existing slash-canonicalisation (so `vertex_ai/gemini-2.5-pro` and `gemini/gemini-2.5-pro` and `google/gemini-2.5-pro` all resolve to `google/gemini-2.5-pro`).\n- Stop using the dotted-vendor split as a key generator (it's lossy — `gemini-3.1-pro-preview` is a model name, not a vendor.model pair).\n- In `model_map.rs::gemini_canonical`, extend the family list to map `gemini-3-flash-preview`, `gemini-3-pro-preview`, `gemini-3.1-pro-preview` to those exact slugs so `model_map`'s output matches a pricing key.\n- In `model_map.rs::openai_canonical`, add `gpt-5.4`, `gpt-5.5` families.\n\n**Acceptance:**\n- Run reckon (after a fresh cache) and confirm the `priced at \\$0` warning no longer lists `gemini-3-flash-preview`, `gemini-3-pro-preview`, `gemini-3.1-pro-preview`, `gpt-5.4`, `gpt-5.5`.\n- The Cost column for those models shows non-zero where pricing-fallback.json has input/output costs.\n- All existing tests in `reckon-core::pricing` and `reckon-core::model_map` continue to pass.\n- Add tests:\n  - `pricing.rs`: `gemini-3-flash-preview` and `gpt-5.5` resolve to non-empty `Pricing`.\n  - `model_map.rs`: `gemini-3-flash-preview`, `gpt-5.5`, and a dated variant `gpt-5.5-2026-04-01` map to the canonical pricing key.","kind":"bug","labels":["pricing","correctness"],"size":"m","title":"Pricing fallback misses gemini-3-* and gpt-5.4/5.5 due to slug mismatch"}	blake3:rWZo2fkpu8B-W6UXCc_zJO9U51g0_38hQtH5sE9ykSQ
1778538788802718	reckon-dev	itc:v3:AWLk8kz5M8ySZQAAAAAAQevVvre1WgAAAAEvvwE		item.create	bn-2cx	{"description":"**Problem:** OpenAI's `total_token_usage` reports `input_tokens` as the **inclusive** count (uncached + cached), and `cached_input_tokens` is the subset that hit prompt cache. `crates/reckon-readers/src/codex.rs::token_counts_from_info` stores raw `input_tokens` as `tokens.input` and raw `cached_input_tokens` as `tokens.cache_read` — so both columns double-count cache hits.\n\nSymptom for May 2026: codex gpt-5.5 reports `In = 3.94B`, `Cache = 3.82B`. True non-cached input is ~120M. Cost math (when prices arrive) would overbill by ~30x.\n\n**Scope:** `crates/reckon-readers/src/codex.rs` only.\n\n- In `token_counts_from_info`, set `input = input_tokens - cached_input_tokens` (saturating_sub for safety).\n- Confirm `delta_counts` math still works (deltas of saturating-subbed values are still monotone).\n- Add a test: feed two synthetic token_count payloads (cumulative) with cache hits, assert the emitted event's `tokens.input` equals the **delta of non-cached** input across the two readings, and `tokens.cache_read` equals the delta of cached.\n- Update any existing codex fixture-based tests if they assumed the current double-counting behavior.\n\n**Acceptance:**\n- `cargo test -p reckon-readers codex` passes.\n- After fix + fresh cache: reckon's May 2026 codex `In` column drops dramatically (closer to a few hundred million), `Cache` stays in the billions, and `In + Cache` ≈ the previous `In` value.\n- No new dependencies.","kind":"bug","labels":["readers","codex","correctness"],"size":"s","title":"Codex reader: input_tokens already includes cached_input_tokens; subtract to avoid inflation"}	blake3:-R2eTHpt4gF8YYWuURwZrT1YcbxmvTyBUE-P2PgxQ-Q
1778538809703510	reckon-dev	itc:v3:AWLk8kz5M8ySZQAAAAAAQevVvre1WgAAAAEvwAE		item.create	bn-1ov	{"description":"**Problem:** Output table is functional but ugly and drops information.\n\n1. `crates/reckon-cli/src/render.rs::build_data_row` only prints `tokens.cache_read` in the `Cache` column. `tokens.cache_write` (Claude's `cache_creation_input_tokens`) is silently dropped from the display, even though it's counted in cost.\n2. Header label `Reason` is opaque — it's reasoning tokens. Rename to `Reasoning`. (Codex/Pi can have huge reasoning counts; the column matters.)\n3. `Style::blank()` gives no separators between month groups and no header underline. The `TOTAL` rows visually blend in with data rows. Wide-number months swamp narrow ones with no breathing room.\n\nUser feedback (verbatim): \"by 'a mess' I actually meant the table is kind of ugly. maybe there are some console output libs we could use to make the tabular output a little more appealing. maybe something like https://crates.io/crates/rich_rust\"\n\n**Scope:** `crates/reckon-cli/src/render.rs` (primary). Tests in same file. May touch `report.rs` only for the cache-write totaling (TokenCounts already has `cache_write`).\n\nApproach:\n\n- **Cache columns:** split into `Cache Wr` and `Cache Rd` (or `CacheCreate` / `CacheRead` — match ccusage's `Cache Create`/`Cache Read` style). Both column headers must be short enough that an 80-col terminal still fits common rows.\n- **Reasoning rename:** `Reason` -> `Reasoning`.\n- **Table style:** replace `Style::blank()` with something more polished. Options in priority order:\n  1. `tabled` already supports `Style::psql()`, `Style::rounded()`, `Style::modern()`. Try `Style::modern()` or `Style::psql()` plus a horizontal separator between each month group (insert a `tabled::settings::style::HorizontalLine` after each month's TOTAL row).\n  2. Acceptable to swap `tabled` for `comfy_table` if it gives a materially better result (UTF8 rounded borders, group separators). Don't add a new dep unless it's a clear win.\n  3. Do NOT add a dep on `rich_rust` (alpha-quality / lightly maintained) — the user named it only as a \"something like\" reference.\n- Color the `TOTAL` row labels distinctly when `use_color` is true (e.g. bold/cyan) so they pop.\n- Money column: right-align (already done), continue `\\${n:.2}`.\n- Keep JSON output stable; the `Cache` column split only affects table rendering. (Actually JSON already exposes cache_write — confirm and leave alone.)\n\n**Acceptance:**\n- `cargo test -p reckon-cli` passes (update snapshot tests as needed — there are snapshots in `crates/reckon-cli/src/snapshots/`).\n- Running `cargo run --bin reckon` prints a visually clearer table: header is visually separated from data, each month group is bordered or separated, TOTAL rows are visually distinct.\n- The table includes a cache-write column with non-zero values for Claude (where `cache_creation_input_tokens` > 0).\n- `Reasoning` header replaces `Reason`.\n- JSON output (`reckon --json`) is unchanged in field names.\n- No regression in `--no-color` output.\n\nInspiration (ccusage Total row shape):\n\n```\nCache Create | Cache Read | Total Tokens | Cost\n85,942,xxx  | 4,607,xxx,xxx | 4,704,xxx,xxx | \\$2967.08\n```","kind":"task","labels":["render","ux"],"size":"m","title":"Improve monthly table aesthetics + show cache-write column + rename 'Reason'"}	blake3:yHLm2_CTygSRZINYhWz25AH4EK9QpHiG9Asv2u-t7-U
