1778544091850892	reckon-dev	itc:v3:AWLk8kz5M8ySZQAAAAAAQevVvre1WgAAAAEv0QE		item.create	bn-wyu	{"description":"**Problem:** reckon currently buckets events into months using UTC (`YearMonth::from_utc(ts_secs)` in every reader). The user is in US/Eastern (UTC-4 EDT). Late-evening local-time work on the last day of a month gets pushed into the next month's bucket. This caused reckon to disagree with ccusage (which uses local time) by hundreds of dollars on the April/May boundary in May 2026: reckon May $3544 vs ccusage May $2997, mirrored by reckon April $7884 vs ccusage April $8030. ~8000+ Claude events straddle the UTC/local boundary on this machine.\n\nThe user has explicitly asked: **default to local time**. UTC should remain available but not default.\n\n**Scope:**\n- `crates/reckon-core/src/lib.rs` (YearMonth — add a timezone-aware constructor).\n- All readers: `claude.rs`, `codex.rs`, `gemini.rs`, `opencode.rs`, `openrouter.rs`, `pi.rs` (each currently calls `YearMonth::from_utc`).\n- `crates/reckon-cli/src/main.rs` (clap arg, plumb through to readers or to a post-scan re-bucketing pass).\n\n**Approach (suggested, may iterate):**\n\n1. Add `--tz <TZ>` flag to the CLI. Values: `local` (default) or `utc`, or an IANA name (e.g. `America/New_York`) — accept all three. `local` resolves from the system at runtime.\n2. Decouple month bucketing from event creation. Each `UsageEvent` should store the **raw timestamp** (epoch seconds) and let the aggregator bucket at display time. That preserves the \"cost at display time\" invariant and makes re-bucketing free when the flag changes. If keeping `month: YearMonth` on the event for backward compatibility is too disruptive, add an additional `timestamp_secs: i64` field and compute the month from it at aggregation time.\n3. Add a dependency on `jiff` or `chrono` (with `clock` feature) for TZ-aware conversion. **Prefer `jiff`** if it's not yet in the tree — smaller, modern, no `tzdata` build dep on Linux (uses `/usr/share/zoneinfo`). Confirm asupersync compatibility (no async needed for this — pure date math).\n4. The cache schema's `events.month` column either becomes `timestamp_secs` (migration), or the cache is invalidated by a schema version bump. Schema migration is cleaner — store `timestamp_secs INTEGER NOT NULL` and drop `month`. Bump the cache schema version (look for existing `PRAGMA user_version` or equivalent in `crates/reckon-core/src/cache.rs`).\n\n**Acceptance:**\n- `reckon` with no args buckets in local time (`US/Eastern` on this machine).\n- `reckon --tz utc` reproduces the old behavior.\n- `reckon --tz America/Los_Angeles` works.\n- Side-by-side: after the change, `reckon --source claude` totals for 2026-04 should be **higher** than before (closer to ccusage's $8030) and 2026-05 should be **lower** (closer to ccusage's $2997).\n- Existing tests pass; add tests covering: local-vs-UTC bucketing of an event at e.g. 2026-05-01T03:00:00Z (UTC May, EDT April).\n- The cache schema migration must not corrupt existing data (or, if simpler, cleanly invalidate the cache and rebuild).\n\n**Out of scope:**\n- DST handling subtleties beyond what `jiff`/`chrono` provides for free.\n- Per-source TZ overrides (one TZ for the whole run is fine).","kind":"bug","labels":["correctness","timezone"],"size":"m","title":"Default month bucketing to local timezone (with --tz flag for UTC)"}	blake3:oKeMVFiSTxMUoUXrc6_AOSeb3jPEm2SksQ1pWUoaYsk
1778544102557201	reckon-dev	itc:v3:AWLk8kz5M8ySZQAAAAAAQevVvre1WgAAAAEv0gE		item.create	bn-3ho	{"description":"**Problem:** `crates/reckon-readers/src/pi.rs::scan_pi_session_file` requires `message.id`, `message.timestamp` (as i64 ms), `message.provider`, and `message.model` all to be present inside the inner `message` object. Current Pi jsonl format puts `id` and `timestamp` at the **top level** of the JSONL entry, and `timestamp` is an ISO 8601 string, not milliseconds. Every record fails the `let Some(message_id) = message.id else { continue }` guard. Reckon's Pi reader returns zero events.\n\nConcrete sample from `~/.pi/agent/sessions/--home-bob-src--/2026-03-16T04-13-32-883Z_*.jsonl`:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"message\",\n  \"id\": \"d2d38003\",\n  \"parentId\": \"d199f96d\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-03-16T04:14:21.321Z\",\n  \"message\": {\n    \"role\": \"assistant\",\n    \"content\": [...],\n    \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n    \"provider\": \"anthropic\",\n    \"model\": \"claude-haiku-4-5\",\n    \"usage\": { \"input\": 10, \"output\": 234, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 4864, \"totalTokens\": ... }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThere are 982 such assistant records on this machine (687 in Feb, 189 in Apr, 104 in May 2026).\n\n**Scope:** `crates/reckon-readers/src/pi.rs` only.\n\n- Change the `PiJsonlLine` / `PiMessage` serde structs so `id` and `timestamp` are read from the **top level**, not from inside `message`.\n- Parse `timestamp` as ISO 8601 string. Reuse `parse_iso8601_to_epoch` from claude.rs (copy it locally if you don't want to add a cross-module import, or — better — extract to `crates/reckon-readers/src/lib.rs` as a pub(crate) helper. **Prefer the extract** — it'll be reused.). Note: pi timestamps include milliseconds (`.321Z`) — current parser truncates them, that's fine.\n- `provider` and `model` stay inside `message` (current behavior is correct there).\n- Update the existing test fixtures in `tests/fixtures/pi/sample.jsonl` to use the new on-disk format so tests reflect reality. Update assertions accordingly.\n- Add a test that loads a fixture in the **new** format and asserts the events come through correctly.\n\n**Acceptance:**\n- After the fix + fresh cache, `cargo run --bin reckon -- --source pi` returns ~982 records aggregating to non-trivial cost across Feb/Apr/May 2026.\n- `cargo test -p reckon-readers pi` passes.\n- Existing dedup test (`dedup_key = format!(\"{}:{}\", session_id, message_id)`) still works — but the source of `message_id` is now the top-level `id`.","kind":"bug","labels":["readers","pi","correctness"],"size":"s","title":"Pi reader misses every event — top-level id/timestamp not inside message"}	blake3:MTzViz_OriwTO6tHOZCdesPBAYSZlWgETl9QsGZ8m_E
1778544116902116	reckon-dev	itc:v3:AWLk8kz5M8ySZQAAAAAAQevVvre1WgAAAAEv0wE		item.create	bn-9ed	{"description":"**Problem:** `crates/reckon-readers/src/opencode.rs` issues this SQL:\n\n```\nSELECT id, session_id, tokens_input, tokens_output, tokens_reasoning,\n       tokens_cache_read, tokens_cache_write, model_id, provider_id, created\nFROM message WHERE created > ?1 ORDER BY created LIMIT 1000\n```\n\nBut the actual OpenCode schema (on this machine, version current as of 2026-05) is:\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE message (\n  id text PRIMARY KEY,\n  session_id text NOT NULL,\n  time_created integer NOT NULL,\n  time_updated integer NOT NULL,\n  data text NOT NULL,\n  ...\n);\n```\n\nThere are no typed token columns and no `created` column. The token data lives in the `data` JSON blob. Sample blob:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"role\": \"assistant\",\n  \"time\": {\"created\": 1769530068966, \"completed\": 1769530072388},\n  \"modelID\": \"claude-opus-4-5\",\n  \"providerID\": \"anthropic\",\n  \"tokens\": {\n    \"input\": 0, \"output\": 159, \"reasoning\": 0,\n    \"cache\": {\"read\": 26400, \"write\": 327}\n  },\n  \"cost\": 0,\n  ...\n}\n```\n\n41,698 message rows on this machine. The current reader's SQL prepare fails immediately and returns zero events.\n\n**Scope:** `crates/reckon-readers/src/opencode.rs` only.\n\n- Change the SQL to: `SELECT id, session_id, time_created, data FROM message WHERE time_created > ?1 ORDER BY time_created LIMIT 1000`.\n- Parse `data` as JSON. Filter to assistant messages (`role == \"assistant\"`). Use:\n  - `tokens.input` -> `tokens.input`\n  - `tokens.output` -> `tokens.output`\n  - `tokens.reasoning` -> `tokens.reasoning`\n  - `tokens.cache.read` -> `tokens.cache_read`\n  - `tokens.cache.write` -> `tokens.cache_write`\n  - `modelID` -> raw model\n  - `providerID` -> provider\n  - `time_created` (or `time.created` inside the JSON — prefer the column since it's already indexed) -> timestamp in ms; convert to seconds with `/1000`.\n  - `cost` field, when present and non-zero, can be stored as `known_cost_usd` (it's the OpenCode-computed cost, which is useful for cross-checking).\n- Skip rows where `tokens.total() == 0` (current reader already does this).\n- The provider field needs to map through `model_map::canonical(Source::OpenCode, raw_model, Some(provider))`.\n\nThe reader also currently has fallback paths for \"legacy\" file-based opencode storage. Those can stay; they're unlikely to be exercised on a machine that has the sqlite db.\n\n- Update the in-test schema (`crates/reckon-readers/src/opencode.rs` test module — search for `CREATE TABLE`) to match the real schema. Test fixtures may need updating.\n\n**Acceptance:**\n- After fix + fresh cache, `cargo run --bin reckon -- --source opencode` returns thousands of records across multiple months and a non-zero cost.\n- `cargo test -p reckon-readers opencode` passes.\n- Pagination still works (the current LIMIT 1000 + WHERE created > last_seen pattern).\n- The `dedup_key` continues to use `format!(\"opencode:{}\", id)` or equivalent so events aren't double-counted across runs.\n\n**Out of scope:**\n- Schema migration support for older OpenCode databases. If a user has the old typed-column schema, that's a future bone.","kind":"bug","labels":["readers","opencode","correctness"],"size":"m","title":"OpenCode reader queries non-existent schema — tokens live in JSON data blob"}	blake3:bLJNLSJtu76hYBHEZk7EfkIacCJAyx6W4lGgav29OBk
